const Q_IRK_1991=[{"id": "objective>IRK>1991>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">'By Him who dominates my soul I swear that you are the Prophet of this nation . . . you will be abused and you will be persecuted. If I should ever live to see that day, I shal surely help the cause of Allah.'  <br/> Who made the statement above?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Muhammad Husayn Haikal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Waraqah b. Nawfal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">'Abdul Muttalib</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Abbas b. Mirdas</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement was made by Waraqah b. Nawfal. He was a cousin of Khadijah (RA), Prophet Muhammad's (SAW) first wife. He was a Christian monk who had knowledge of the previous scriptures and had predicted the coming of a prophet in Arabia. When Prophet Muhammad (SAW) received his first revelation, Khadijah (RA) took him to Waraqah who confirmed his prophethood.</div>", "topic": "THE LIFE OF PROPHET MUHAMMAD (SAW) : HIS CALL TO PROPHETHOOD"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The ninth year of hijrah is known as the year of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Deputation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elephant</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peace </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Aqabah</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The ninth year of hijrah is known as the year of Deputation. This is because it was in this year that various tribes and communities sent their representatives to Madinah to learn about Islam and the Prophet Muhammad (SAW). These deputations resulted in many conversions to Islam.</div>", "topic": "THE LIFE OF PROPHET MUHAMMAD (SAW) : THE HIJRAH"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">After the Prophet (S.A.W.) had migrated to al-Madinah, the first two major wars he fought against the Makkans were </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Badr and hudaybiyyah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Uhud and Khaybar</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Khandaq and Mu'tah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Badr and Uhud</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">After the Prophet (S.A.W.) had migrated to al-Madinah, the first two major wars he fought against the Makkans were Badr and Uhud. The Battle of Badr was the first major battle, which took place in the second year of Hijrah. The Battle of Uhud was the second major battle, which took place in the third year of Hijrah.</div>", "topic": "THE LIFE OF PROPHET MUHAMMAD (SAW) : THE BATTLES OF BADR, UHUD AND KHANDAQ: CAUSES AND EFFECTS"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Prophet's uncle who lost his life in the battle of Badr was </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hamzah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">'Abbas</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Abu Talib</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Abu Jahl</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Prophet's uncle who lost his life in the battle of Badr was Hamzah. Hamzah was a staunch supporter of Prophet Muhammad (SAW) and was known for his bravery. He was martyred in the Battle of Uhud, not Badr, by Wahshi ibn Harb, a slave who was promised freedom by Jubayr ibn Mut'im if he killed Hamzah.</div>", "topic": "THE LIFE OF PROPHET MUHAMMAD (SAW) : THE BATTLES OF BADR, UHUD AND KHANDAQ: CAUSES AND EFFECTS"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Quraysh boycotted Banu Hashim because they </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">had all accepted Islam</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">refused to accept Islam</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">planned to migrate to Yathrib with the Prophet (S.A.W.)</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">protected the Prophet (S.A.W.) and refused to surrender him</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Quraysh boycotted Banu Hashim because they protected the Prophet (S.A.W.) and refused to surrender him. This boycott was a social and economic embargo against the Muslims and the clan of Banu Hashim, who were mostly Muslims. The boycott lasted for three years and was lifted when the document enforcing the boycott was found to be eaten by termites except for the name of Allah.</div>", "topic": "THE LIFE OF PROPHET MUHAMMAD (SAW) : HIS CALL TO PROPHETHOOD"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The success of the business venture which Muhammad (S.A.W.) carried out for Khadijah was due mainly to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Khadijah's love for him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the fact that he was a prophet</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">his dedication and honesty</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the skill and hard work of his assistants </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The success of the business venture which Muhammad (S.A.W.) carried out for Khadijah was due mainly to his dedication and honesty. Muhammad (S.A.W.) was known for his honesty and integrity, which earned him the nickname Al-Amin, meaning 'the trustworthy'. His honesty in business dealings attracted more customers and brought success to the business.</div>", "topic": "THE LIFE OF PROPHET MUHAMMAD (SAW) : HIS CALL TO PROPHETHOOD"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The social reforms witnessed by Arabia during the life time of the Prophet (S.A.W.) included the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">abolition of slave ownership</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">improvement in slave/master relations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">modification of the practice of infanticide </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">universal recognition of the Arabs as the superior race </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">improvement in slave/master relations. <br/>  <br/> While slavery was not completely abolished during the Prophet's time, Islam significantly improved the treatment of slaves, promoting humane and just relations between slaves and their masters, encouraging the freeing of slaves, and establishing rights for them.</div>", "topic": "ISLAMIC HISTORY AND CIVILIZATION - PRE-ISLAMIC ARABIA JAHILIYYAH : ISLAMIC REFORMS"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The treaty of al-Hudaybiyyah was expected to last </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ten years </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">three years </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ten months </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">six months </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The treaty of al-Hudaybiyyah was expected to last ten years. This treaty was signed between the Prophet Muhammad (S.A.W.) and the Quraysh of Mecca in 628 AD. The terms of the treaty included a ten-year truce and the agreement that Muslims could perform the pilgrimage the following year.</div>", "topic": "THE LIFE OF PROPHET MUHAMMAD (SAW) : THE TREATY OF AL-HUDAIBIYYAH AND THE CONQUEST OF MAKKAH"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Khulafa al-Rashidun reigned between</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A.D. 632 and 661</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A.D. 622 and 632</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A.D. 610 and 661</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A.D. 632 and 750</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Khulafa al-Rashidun, also known as the Rightly Guided Caliphs, reigned between A.D. 632 and 661. This period started with the caliphate of Abu Bakr after the death of Prophet Muhammad (S.A.W.) in 632 AD and ended with the assassination of Ali, the fourth caliph, in 661 AD.</div>", "topic": "THE RIGHTLY GUIDED CALIPHS AL-KHULAFA'U RASHIDUN : THE LIVES AND CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE FOUR RIGHTLY GUIDED CALIPHS"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The conversion of 'Umar b. al-Khattab was a turning point in the history of Islam because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it encouraged the actualization of the Prophet's mission</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the entire Quraysh were immediately converted to Islam</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he publicly announced his migration to al-Madinah and was not challenged</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the boycott of Banu Hashim was terminated</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The conversion of 'Umar b. al-Khattab was a turning point in the history of Islam because it encouraged the actualization of the Prophet's mission. 'Umar was a strong and influential man in Mecca, and his conversion to Islam gave the Muslim community more confidence and strength. His conversion also led to an increase in the number of people accepting Islam.</div>", "topic": "THE LIFE OF PROPHET MUHAMMAD (SAW) : HIS CALL TO PROPHETHOOD"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The battle of Siffin led to the emergence of the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Khawarij</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ahl al-Sunnah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Munafiqun</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Umayyads</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Battle of Siffin was a significant event in Islamic history that led to the emergence of the Khawarij. The Khawarij were a group of extremists who seceded from the main body of Muslims due to their disagreement with the arbitration process that was agreed upon to resolve the conflict between Caliph Ali and Muawiyah, the governor of Syria. They believed in the absolute authority of the Quran and rejected any form of human arbitration.</div>", "topic": "THE LIFE OF PROPHET MUHAMMAD (SAW) : THE BATTLES OF BADR, UHUD AND KHANDAQ: CAUSES AND EFFECTS"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During the reign of Caliph 'Ali, the seat of administration moved from al-Madinah to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Basra </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Damascus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Mecca </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Kufah</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During the reign of Caliph 'Ali, the seat of administration moved from al-Madinah to Kufah. Kufah was a city in present-day Iraq. Ali moved his capital to Kufah in order to have a strategic advantage during the civil war that was taking place during his caliphate.</div>", "topic": "THE RIGHTLY GUIDED CALIPHS AL-KHULAFA'U RASHIDUN : THE LIVES AND CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE FOUR RIGHTLY GUIDED CALIPHS"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The first Quranic verse revealed, instructed the Prophet (S.A.W.) to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">engage in preaching and warning</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">seek knowledge through reading </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">keep vigil the night long</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">read the minds of people</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The first Quranic verse revealed was 'Read in the name of your Lord who created' (Surah Al-Alaq, 96:1). This verse instructed the Prophet Muhammad (S.A.W.) to seek knowledge through reading. This marked the beginning of the revelation of the Quran which continued for 23 years until the death of the Prophet.</div>", "topic": "THE QUR’AN AND HADITH – REVELATION OF THE GLORIOUS QUR’AN : HIS REACTION TO THE FIRST REVELATION AND ITS IMPORTANCE"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The surah that tells us the story of how the Ka'abah was delivered from destruction is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">al-Fatihah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">al-Alaq</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">al-Fil</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Abasa</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Surah that tells us the story of how the Ka'abah was delivered from destruction is Surah al-Fil. This Surah narrates the incident of the 'People of the Elephant' who intended to destroy the Ka'abah but were defeated and their plan was thwarted by birds sent by Allah who dropped stones on them.</div>", "topic": "THE QUR'AN AND HADITH - REVELATION OF THE GLORIOUS QUR'AN : DIFFERENT MODES OF REVELATION: INSPIRATION BEHIND THE VEIL, THROUGH AN ANGEL, ETC."}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Surat an-Nas, protection was sought from the evils of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">men and women</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">husband and wife </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">men and jinn</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">male and female </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Surat an-Nas, protection is sought from the evils of men and jinn. The Surah is a prayer for protection from the evil whispers and suggestions of Satan, who is described as whispering into the hearts of men and jinn. It is the last Surah of the Quran and is often recited for protection from evil.</div>", "topic": "ARTICLE OF FAITH : BELIEF IN ALLAH"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Refence to a special night is made in Surat</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ad-Duha</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">al-Tin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">al-Falaq</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">al-Qadr</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Surat al-Qadr refers to the special night, which is Laylat al-Qadr, the Night of Decree. This night is considered the holiest night of the year for Muslims, and is traditionally celebrated on the 27th day of Ramadan. It is known as the night when the first verses of the Quran were revealed to the Prophet Muhammad.</div>", "topic": "STUDY OF THE ARABIC TEXT OF THE FOLLOWING SUWAR/AYATS WITH TAJWID : AL-QADR"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The verse Wa la sawfa yu tika rabbuka fatarda is immediately preceded by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a lam yajidka yatiman fa awa</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wa rafa na laka dhikraka </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Walal-akhiratu khayrun laka minal ida </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">thumma latus alunna yawma idhin anin-na im</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The verse \"Wa la sawfa yuʿṭīka rabbuka fa-tarḍā\" (Qur'an 93:5) is immediately preceded by: <br/>  <br/> \"Wal-ākhiratu khayrun laka mina l-ūlā\" (Qur'an 93:4)</div>", "topic": "STUDY OF THE ARABIC TEXT OF THE FOLLOWING SUWAR/AYATS WITH TAJWID : AD-DUHA"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A Makkan surah with the main objective of reassuring the Prophet (S.A.W.) at a time of distress is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at-Takathur</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ad-Duha</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">al-Kafirun</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">al-ma un</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Surah Ad-Duha was revealed in Makkah and it is a Makkan Surah. The main objective of this Surah was to reassure the Prophet (S.A.W.) at a time of distress and grief due to the pause in revelation. The Surah reassures the Prophet that Allah has not abandoned him.</div>", "topic": "STUDY OF THE ARABIC TEXT OF THE FOLLOWING SUWAR/AYATS WITH TAJWID : AD-DUHA"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The verse (Q. 17. 23) <img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/>  warns against </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">insulting parents </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">underfeeding parents </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">beating parents </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">deserting parents </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The verse Qur'an 17:23 warns against being disrespectful or disobedient to one's parents by insulting them.</div>", "topic": "MORAL LESSONS IN THE GLORIOUS QUR'AN AND HADITH : GOODNESS TO PARENTS"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Suratul-Kawthar concerns the Prophet's </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">birthday</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">marriage to Khadijah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loss of his son</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">triumphant entry into Makkah</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Suratul-Kawthar concerns the Prophet's loss of his son. The Surah was revealed after the death of the Prophet's son, Abdullah. The disbelievers of Makkah rejoiced at this personal loss of the Prophet, and this Surah was revealed as a consolation to the Prophet, assuring him that he indeed had been granted 'Al-Kawthar' (abundance of good).</div>", "topic": "STUDY OF THE ARABIC TEXT OF THE FOLLOWING SUWAR/AYATS WITH TAJWID : AL -KAWTHAR"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the verse Ya ayyuhal -ladhina amanu la taqrabus-salata wa antum sukara (Q. 4. 43) Allah is asking the Muslims not to attempt to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sleep when it is prayer time</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pray when they are intoxicated </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">eat when they are in prayer </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pray when at war </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the verse 'Ya ayyuhal -ladhina amanu la taqrabus-salata wa antum sukara' (Q. 4. 43), Allah is asking the Muslims not to attempt to pray when they are intoxicated. The verse translates to 'O you who have believed, do not approach prayer while you are intoxicated until you know what you are saying.' This verse was revealed to ensure that Muslims are in a clear state of mind during their prayers.</div>", "topic": "IBADAT AND THEIR TYPES : SALAH"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The verse  <img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/>  (Q. 95.8) means 'Is Allah not'</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a good Judge?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">our Judge?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the best of Judges?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Head of all Judges?</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Qur'an 95:8 (Surah At-Tin, verse 8) says: <br/>  <br/> \"Alaysa Allahu bi-ahkamil ḥākimīn?\" <br/> \"Is not Allah the best of judges?\" <br/>  <br/> It is a rhetorical question.</div>", "topic": "STUDY OF THE ARABIC TEXT OF THE FOLLOWING SUWAR/AYATS WITH TAJWID : AT-TIN"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The official compilation of Hadith was initiated by </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Abu Bakr al-Siddiq</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">'Umar b. al-khattab <br/> </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">'Umar b. Abd al-Aziz</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Harun ar-Rashid</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The official compilation of Hadith was initiated by 'Umar b. Abd al-Aziz. He was the first caliph to order the collection of Hadiths, which were the sayings and actions of Prophet Muhammad.</div>", "topic": "HADITH : HISTORY OF HADITH LITERATURE -COLLECTION OF HADITH FROM THE TIME OF THE PROPHET-SAW TO THE PERIOD OF THE SIX AUTHENTIC COLLECTORS OF HADITH"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The difference between isnad and matn is that </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">matn is the chain of reporters, while isnad is their quality</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">isnad is the chain of reporters while matn is the text</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">isnad is more important than matn</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">isnad refers to the reliability of the reporters while matn refers to their weaknesses</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isnad and Matn are two components of a Hadith. Isnad is the chain of reporters or narrators who transmitted the Hadith from the Prophet Muhammad to the collector of the Hadith. Matn, on the other hand, is the actual text of the Hadith or the content of the message.</div>", "topic": "HADITH : AUTHENTICATION OF HADITH"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Hadith \". . .<img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> \"   teaches that a Muslim</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">must obey the commands of the Prophet (S.A.W.)</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">must confine himself to the established teachings of Islam</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">can contribute in developing and increasing the teachings of Islam</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">should always command what is good </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Hadith teaches that a Muslim must confine himself to the established teachings of Islam.</div>", "topic": "HADITH : THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN HADITH AND THE GLORIOUS QUR’AN"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The expression 'Man kana yu minu billahi wal yawmil akhir fal yaqul khayran aw li yasmut' means a believer should </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">desire for his neighbour what he wishes for himself </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">never be angry</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">make good utterances or keep silent </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">honour his parents </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The expression 'Man kana yu minu billahi wal yawmil akhir fal yaqul khayran aw li yasmut' translates to 'Whoever believes in Allah and the Last Day should speak good or keep silent'. This Hadith emphasizes the importance of controlling one's speech and only speaking what is beneficial.</div>", "topic": "HADITH : THE STUDY OF THE ARABIC TEXTS OF THE FOLLOWING AHADITH FROMAN-NAWAWI’S COLLECTION: 1,3,5,6,7,9,10,11,12,13,15,16, 18,19,21,22,25,27,34, AND 41"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">'Verily Allah has prescribed the best behaviour with regard to everything...' <br/> The above quotation from Hadith 17 of an-Nawawi's collection emphasizes the ethics of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">eating and drinking</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">slaughtering animals </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">behaving in public </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">matrimonial relations</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The quotation from Hadith 17 of an-Nawawi's collection emphasizes the ethics of slaughtering animals. It teaches that when one slaughters an animal, they should do it in the most humane way.</div>", "topic": "HADITH : THE STUDY OF THE ARABIC TEXTS OF THE FOLLOWING AHADITH FROMAN-NAWAWI’S COLLECTION: 1,3,5,6,7,9,10,11,12,13,15,16, 18,19,21,22,25,27,34, AND 41"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following does NOT belong to the group?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Muslim b. al-Hajjaj</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Abdullah b. 'Umar</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Abdullah b. Mas ud</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Umar b. al-Khattab</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Muslim b. al-Hajjaj does not belong to the group. The other three, Abdullah b. 'Umar, Abdullah b. Mas ud, and Umar b. al-Khattab, were companions of the Prophet Muhammad. Muslim b. al-Hajjaj, however, was a later Islamic scholar known for his collection of Hadith, Sahih Muslim.</div>", "topic": "HADITH : THE SIX SOUND COLLECTORS OF HADITH – BIOGRAPHIES AND THEIR WORKS."}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Prophet described as ruhullah in the Qur an is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Musa</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isa</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ibrahim</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isma il</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Qur'an, Prophet Isa (Jesus) is referred to as 'Ruhullah', which means 'Spirit of God'. Therefore, the correct answer is Isa.</div>", "topic": "ARTICLE OF FAITH : HIS PROPHETS: ULUL-AZMI"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/>   <br/> The above extract from Hadith No. 1 of an- Nawawi is followed by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/>  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/>  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/>  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/>  </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hadith No. 1 of An-Nawawi's 40 Hadith is the famous narration on intentions: <br/>  <br/> \"Innamal a'maalu bin-niyyaat...\" <br/> \"Actions are judged by intentions...\"</div>", "topic": "HADITH : THE STUDY OF THE ARABIC TEXTS OF THE FOLLOWING AHADITH FROMAN-NAWAWI’S COLLECTION: 1,3,5,6,7,9,10,11,12,13,15,16, 18,19,21,22,25,27,34, AND 41"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The main function of angel Azra il is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">carrying messages to the Prophets </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">causing rain to fall</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">keeping the gate of Hell</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">taking the lives of people</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Islamic tradition, Angel Azra'il is known as the Angel of Death, whose main function is to take the souls of people at the time of death. Therefore, the correct answer is 'taking the lives of people'.</div>", "topic": "ARTICLE OF FAITH : BELIEF IN ALLAH'S ANGELS"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Prophet Isa spoke in the cradle and </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cleared the conscience of the people </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exonerated his mother </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">performed other miracles </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sillenced the people </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Qur'an, when Prophet Isa (Jesus) was in the cradle, he spoke to protect his mother, Maryam, from the accusations of the people. Therefore, the correct answer is 'exonerated his mother'.</div>", "topic": "ARTICLE OF FAITH : HIS PROPHETS: ULUL-AZMI"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The five most important prophets in Islam were </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Yahya Zakariyya Dawud Sulayman Adam </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Muhammad Nuh Ibrahim, Musa, Isa </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Muhammad, Nuh, Dhul-kifl, Idris Harun</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ibrahim, Musa Isa Adam Ayyub</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The five most important prophets in Islam, known as 'Ulul Azm', are Prophet Muhammad, Nuh (Noah), Ibrahim (Abraham), Musa (Moses), and Isa (Jesus). Therefore, the correct answer is 'Muhammad, Nuh, Ibrahim, Musa, Isa'.</div>", "topic": "ARTICLE OF FAITH : HIS PROPHETS: ULUL-AZMI"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following Prophets, according to the Quran, lived for not less than nine hundred and fifty years?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Adam</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nuh</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ibrahim</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Musa</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Qur'an, Prophet Nuh (Noah) lived for 950 years. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Nuh'.</div>", "topic": "ARTICLE OF FAITH : HIS PROPHETS: ULUL-AZMI"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following Prophets was an ancestor of both Arabs and Jews?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isa </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Dawud </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ayyub</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ibrahim</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Prophet Ibrahim (Abraham) is considered an ancestor of both Arabs and Jews. According to Islamic tradition, his first son, Ismail (Ishmael), is the ancestor of the Arab people, while his second son, Ishaq (Isaac), is the ancestor of the Jewish people.</div>", "topic": "ARTICLE OF FAITH : BELIEF IN ALLAH'S PROPHETS: ULUL-AZMI"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Iddah, the waiting period after a divorce, is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">forty days </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">three months </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">five months </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">three years </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Iddah is the waiting period a woman must observe after the death of her spouse or after a divorce, during which she may not marry another man. Its purpose is to ensure that the male parent of any offspring produced after the cessation of a nikah (marriage) would be known. The standard waiting period of Iddah is three menstrual cycles or three months.</div>", "topic": "FAMILY MATTERS : DIVORCE"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Performing Tayammum is justified when one </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">does not like to touch water </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is on a journey</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is sick</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is in a hurry</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tayammum is a dry ablution in Islamic ritual purification for prayer, which can be used as a substitute for ritual washing (wudu or ghusl) if clean water is not available or if one is sick and unable to use water. It involves the use of clean soil or dust.</div>", "topic": "IBADAT AND THEIR TYPES : TAHARAH, ITS TYPES AND IMPORTANCE AL-ISTINJA'/ISTIJMAR, ALWUDU', AT-TAYAMMUM AND AL-GHUSL HADITH 10 AND 23 OF AN-NAWAWI"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sawn is the abstinence from eating, drinking and sexual urge </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">from dawn to dusk without intention of worship</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">from morning to evening in times of distress </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">with or without the intention of worship</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">from dawn to dusk with the intention of worship</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sawn is the practice of fasting, particularly during the month of Ramadan, where Muslims abstain from eating, drinking, and sexual activities from dawn (Fajr) to dusk (Maghrib) with the intention of worship. The intention (niyyah) is a necessary component of the fast.</div>", "topic": "IBADAT AND THEIR TYPES : SAWM"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In order to make Tawaf, you are required to keep the ka abah to your </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">left and go round it in an anticlockwise direction </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">right and go round it in a clockwise direction </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">left and go round it in a clockwise direction </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">right and move round it in an anticlockwise direction</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tawaf is one of the Islamic rituals of pilgrimage. During the Hajj and Umrah, Muslims are to go around the Ka'bah (the most sacred site in Islam) seven times, in a counterclockwise direction; the first three circuits at a hurried pace on the outer part of the crowd, followed by four times, more closely, at a leisurely pace. The Ka'bah should be on the left side of the person performing Tawaf.</div>", "topic": "IBADAT AND THEIR TYPES : HAJJ"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The verse  <img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/>   <br/> means that divorce may be pronounced twice and then the woman must </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">go after the third time </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be retained in honour or allowed to go with kindness </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">forfeit her wealth and go with kindness </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be retained in honour unless she has no children</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Divorce may be pronounced twice and then the woman must be retained in honour or allowed to go with kindness.</div>", "topic": "FAMILY MATTERS : DIVORCE"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the conditions of Sunni talaq is that it must be pronounced </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">three time consecutively</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">by the mother-in-law </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">when the wife is free from menstruation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">with the free consent of the wife </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Sunni Islam, one of the conditions for a valid talaq (divorce) is that the wife must be in a state of purity, i.e., she must be free from menstruation. This is because menstruation is considered a period of physical and emotional discomfort for women, and decisions made during this time may not be clear or rational. Therefore, to ensure fairness and justice, talaq should be pronounced when the wife is free from menstruation.</div>", "topic": "FAMILY MATTERS : DIVORCE"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The first tawaf which a pilgrim makes when he arrives at Makkah is called tawaf</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">al-ifadah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">al-qudum</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ar-rukn</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">al-wida </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Islamic pilgrimage (Hajj), the first tawaf (circumambulation of the Kaaba) that a pilgrim performs upon arriving in Makkah is called Tawaf al-Qudum. This is an introductory tawaf meant to respect the sanctity of Makkah and the Kaaba.</div>", "topic": "IBADAT AND THEIR TYPES : HAJJ"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If instead of four raka 'at a devotee observes five raka at in salat az-Zuhr he should perform</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ba'diyyah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Qabliyyah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ibadiyyah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sanusiyyah</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If instead of four raka 'at a devotee observes five raka at in salat az-Zuhr he should perform Ba'diyyah.</div>", "topic": "IBADAT AND THEIR TYPES : SALAH"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Having met all the conditions for the payment of Zakah, Mallam Ibrahim has five hundred Niara. How much should he pay as Zakah from this amount?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">N50.10k</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">N16.50k</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">N15.50k</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">N12.50k</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The standard percentage of Zakāh (obligatory almsgiving in Islam) is 2.5% (or 1/40) of a Muslim's qualifying wealth that has been held for one lunar year (ḥawl).</div>", "topic": "IBADAT AND THEIR TYPES : ZAKAH"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A worshipper who remembers that he missed an obligatory step of ablution after he had finished praying will have to repeat</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">only the ablution</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">only the obligatory step</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">nothing after all</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the ablution and the prayer</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Islam, ablution (wudu) is a prerequisite for performing the prayer (Salat). If a worshipper remembers that he missed an obligatory step of ablution after he had finished praying, he will have to repeat both the ablution and the prayer. This is because the prayer performed without a proper ablution is not valid.</div>", "topic": "IBADAT AND THEIR TYPES : TAHARAH, ITS TYPES AND IMPORTANCE AL-ISTINJA'/ISTIJMAR, ALWUDU', AT-TAYAMMUM AND AL-GHUSL HADITH 10 AND 23 OF AN-NAWAWI"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The 'Iddah period of a pregnant woman terminates at the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">time of delivery</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">end of the third month of delivery </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">end of the mourning period </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">end of the third menstruation</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The 'Iddah period for a pregnant woman in Islam ends at the time of delivery. 'Iddah is a waiting period that a woman must observe after the death of her spouse or after a divorce, during which she may not marry another man. Its purpose is to ensure that the male parent of any offspring produced after the cessation of a nikah (marriage) would be known.</div>", "topic": "FAMILY MATTERS : MARRIAGE"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Of all the special prayers salat al-Janazah is unique because it lacks </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">takbir </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">taslim</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ruku</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wudu</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Salat al-Janazah is a special prayer in Islam that is performed at a funeral. It is unique because it lacks ruku (bowing). In this prayer, there is no physical movement of bowing or prostrating, it is mainly a prayer of supplication for the deceased.</div>", "topic": "IBADAT AND THEIR TYPES : SALAH"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Apart from the cleanliness of the body and clothes, the devotee who intends to pray must also ensure the cleanliness of the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">soul</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">place </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">qiblah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">water</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Apart from the cleanliness of the body and clothes, the devotee who intends to pray must also ensure the cleanliness of the place. This is because in Islam, cleanliness is considered half of faith and it is a prerequisite for prayers. The place of prayer must be clean from any impurities.</div>", "topic": "IBADAT AND THEIR TYPES : SALAH"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A father or guardian can give out his daughter or ward in marriage under the principle of Ijbar provided that the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">girl has attained the age of maturity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mother is properly informed </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">girl is a minor</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">groom does not have any physical disability</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ijbar is an Islamic legal principle that gives a wali (guardian) — typically the father — the authority to contract marriage on behalf of his minor daughter or ward, without her explicit consent.</div>", "topic": "FAMILY MATTERS : MARRIAGE"}, {"id": "objective>IRK>1991>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sadaq is the exclusive property of the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">husband </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wife </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bride's family</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">husband and wife </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sadaq is the exclusive property of the wife. Sadaq, also known as Mahr, is a mandatory gift given by the groom to the bride at the time of marriage. It becomes the exclusive property of the wife and she can use it as she pleases.</div>", "topic": "FAMILY MATTERS : MARRIAGE"}];
